    <text>
        <body>
        	<div1 type="letter">
        		<pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0077"/>
        		<head>Jim to Mlle. Marcelle Guerin <date value="1915-05">may-1915</date></head>
        		
        		<opener>
            <dateline><date value="1915-05">may-1915</date></dateline>
        		</opener>
        		
        		<p>
            Even tho [sic] friend Enos
            is in a hurry to get
            to England, en route to
            America, I am positive that
            he will take the time 
            to see you and so
            I am sending this
            note by him.  There
            is no use giving you
            news for Curtin will
            narrate all of it &mdash; and
            more, I’m sure, so
            I’ll just send a few 
            lines to say &mdash; Hello.
        		</p>
        		<p>
            I’ve moved up from
            our base at Dieulouard
            where I had a billet
            and am located all the
            time now at Pont a Mousson.
            There has been a general

            <pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0078" n="[p.2]"/>
            
            exodus from this town
            and as a result I
            have a most delightful
            billet in an exceedingly
            comfortable apartment.
            Ned Salisbury, or Chief, 
            and I share the suite
            of rooms together.  From
            my window I can look
            across the green Moselle
            to the quaint hill of
            Mousson topped by the
            ancient castle of the 
            Duke of Lorraine.  Remarkable
            fortune we’re having, for
            in addition to our
            comfortable quarters here
            we have the caserne
            across the way where
            our outfit is located.
            
            <pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0079" n="[p.3]"/>
            
            Just en face is the
            most superb and 
            exquisite garden I’ve
            ever seen and I stroll
            there sometimes &mdash;
            alas, alone.  Seems such
            a pity to waste these 
            moonlight nights.  There
            are nightingales too, &mdash;
            mais c’est la guerre.
        		</p>
        		<p>
            Can’t you get assigned
            to our section as Red
            Cross Nurse?  I’ll guarantee
            to get wounded and then you can wheel me
            around the gravel
            paths of the aforementioned
            garden.
        		</p>
        		<p>
            Went up into Le Bois le
            Pretre the other day and
            
            <pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0080" n="[p.4]"/>
            
            thru [sic] the mutilated
            Quart en Reserve to
            the first line trench.
            The Germans are but
            50 meters distant there.
            Was dressed as a 
            French soldier.
        		</p>
        		<p>
            Don’t let Enos cut
            me out entirely and
            to relieve my worry 
            drop me a line after
            you’ve told him good-
            bye.
        		</p>
        		
        		<closer>
            <signed>Jim</signed>
        		</closer>
        		
            
